author: UsingYourWifi
body:
> The overwhelming majority of these unemployed are low wage workers who couldn't afford a $4K stationary bike anyway. And now they are receiving unemployment which will prop them up for a few months.

I'd say a plurality, not an overwhelming majority. [Did you look at the per-sector numbers in the ADP report](https://www.cnbc.com/2020/05/06/adp-private-payrolls-april-2020-drop-by-record-20point2-million.html)? The hospitality sector wasn't even half of the 20.2 million job losses.

> Trade, transportation and utilities was the next hardest-hit sector, losing 3.44 million, while construction dropped 2.48 million. **Other big losses came in manufacturing (1.67 million)**, the other services category (1.3 million), and **professional and business services (1.17 million)**. Health care and social assistance plunged by 999,000, **information services fell by 309,000** and **financial services had 216,000 layoffs.**

Record-breaking losses in industries that are not low-wage. 

Furthermore, that isn't the whole story. My cushy 6 figure job that lets me furnish every one of my downtown penthouse apartments with matching $4k exercise bikes for my wife and I is paid for by low-wage workers buying the crap my employer sells them. Low wage workers are getting shit on now though, so I'm going to hold off on buying bikes for my wife's boyfriend. My spending is through the floor right now and I don't care how open shit gets, it's not going up until I'm confident my employer is in the clear.

If it was made by ADP, then ADP should experience significant revenue drop, unless they can make money from the filling of layoffs and unemployment benefits

Essentially, ADP could experience a huge reversal in payroll filing

author: UsingYourWifi
body:
I think you're right that unemployment payments are going to be a much bigger gap-filler than most people believe. That $600/week is a massive stimulus. If we'd had that in 2008 the recovery might not have been so lethargic, and so slow to benefit the middle and lower class. If the proposed $2k/week to everyone were to pass (it won't) I'd become the biggest, Chaddiest bull this sub had ever seen.

However, you're very wrong that "jobs that actually matter are hardly affected." [Did you look at the per-sector numbers in the ADP report](https://www.cnbc.com/2020/05/06/adp-private-payrolls-april-2020-drop-by-record-20point2-million.html)? The hospitality sector wasn't even half of the 20.2 million job losses.

> Trade, transportation and utilities was the next hardest-hit sector, losing 3.44 million, while construction dropped 2.48 million. **Other big losses came in manufacturing (1.67 million)**, the other services category (1.3 million), and **professional and business services (1.17 million)**. Health care and social assistance plunged by 999,000, **information services fell by 309,000** and **financial services had 216,000 layoffs.**

To put that in context the manufacturing job losses *alone* are double the largest month of total job losses in history (834k in 2009). Many of those other sectors are white collar office worker jobs, and they are also crushing the total job loss number record.

> The people that are unemployed right now are people who could just as easily be replaced with a machine or a monkey. People who stand at a register and scan items. They are the lifeblood of a dead and bloated retail world and the coronavirus is the bullet to the brain to put this beast out of its misery. The market goes up when the dead weight companies go under

Layoffs aren't limited to retail as evidenced by the ADP reports. And this administration and the Fed's printers aren't going to let dead companies go under no matter how much they deserve to. 

Now, the effect any form of economic armageddon has on the market is anyone's guess. They're loosely correlated at best and the Fed is doing its best to destroy any sort of price discovery.

author: DANNYBOYLOVER
body:
\#1 Upselling free users.  One example of a conversion: After a certain amount of survey responses you need a premium account.  Turning even one or two percent free users to paid users would increase revenue by close to 32%.  Survey usage has been up significantly over the past several weeks and is reflected in google analytic searches.

\#2 Scaling their enterprise solutions.  This is the biggest opportunity for $$ them.  Their biggest challenge in Q4 2019 was to show that their enterprise business was scaleable and that people would actually integrate it with their current CRM systems.  And they did.  It increased 121% YoY.  The only reason I can see for them to be where theyre at currently is bceause of the COVID-19 crisis.

THey are much easier to use and more intuitive than their competitors like, Qualtrics for example.

Also, you have to think what’s gonna be big in the next five years. Cloud computing (AMZN, MSFT, GOOG, ADBE, and NVDA for hardware), enterprise tech platforms (MSFT, CRM, GOOG, ADBE, even AAPL and FB), video games (EA, ATVI, MSFT, NVDA, and FB has oculus)... I can continue but you get it. 

Tech has a lower cost for growth and the lowest entry threshold for obtaining economies of scale than physical retailers or businesses with complex supply chains.
